    {
      "id": "ZVc7gN-du0Al9tUUQqTlI",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1218.262764546342,
      "y": 44270.29396455291,
      "width": 1122,
      "height": 250,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bcL",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 84950026,
      "version": 1018,
      "versionNonce": 237279434,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773646904456,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Rahul user has a permission to create a VM instance that is user to service permission\nRahul is a part of devops team and devOps group has a permission to create S3 bucket another resource.\nTo create database we need permission third one is service to service\nwhich means have I given to my EC2 service permission to interact with DB service or not, If I have\nnot given permission my EC2 wont be able to communicate to database there is a layer of security.\nBy giving permissions only we are allowing them to communicate with one another.\nSo this is how permission work, Permission have how many type , we will learn as we learn AWS.\n\nFor example -> Permission to create a resource, List all the details of that resource or execute the\nresource or delete the resource, there are lot of type of permissions that we see in cloud.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Rahul user has a permission to create a VM instance that is user to service permission\nRahul is a part of devops team and devOps group has a permission to create S3 bucket another resource.\nTo create database we need permission third one is service to service\nwhich means have I given to my EC2 service permission to interact with DB service or not, If I have\nnot given permission my EC2 wont be able to communicate to database there is a layer of security.\nBy giving permissions only we are allowing them to communicate with one another.\nSo this is how permission work, Permission have how many type , we will learn as we learn AWS.\n\nFor example -> Permission to create a resource, List all the details of that resource or execute the\nresource or delete the resource, there are lot of type of permissions that we see in cloud.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "eAr556_-atpwsln4dWSXn",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1142.743233296342,
      "y": 44579.72365205291,
      "width": 935,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bcN",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 892890698,
      "version": 126,
      "versionNonce": 1017987734,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773646976914,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Now we move to creating our first resource and leaving a larger footprint on our VPC?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Now we move to creating our first resource and leaving a larger footprint on our VPC?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "zzRymVR9cK2NNfJx_Uqtn",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1186.215889546342,
      "y": 44633.49318330291,
      "width": 1309,
      "height": 2775,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bcP",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1386353942,
      "version": 8048,
      "versionNonce": 1616874762,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773657705571,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "We all with start with IAAS for this purpose\n1 login to cloud account or root user\n2 make sure we are in our nearest region if we are in India we must be in mumbai region (APAC) asia\n    pasific region\n3 Now we will create our 1st EC2(Elastic Compute Cloud) instance, search in services for EC2 and go inside that then in\n    dashboard we get launch instance\n    one way is we can crate EC2 instance by launching instance\n    second way is we can check if there is any existing instance, existing VMs created or not, In terminology\n    of AWS we will call our VMs as our instance. \n    \n    for new instance we will click on launch instance\n    \n    give name -> tryserver or anything that we want to give\n\n    second thing is when we have installed Virtual Machine, we didn't only need Oracle Virtual Box or any\nhypervisor we also needed something called as a ISO file.\nwe can choose our ISO, here we will choose Ubuntu  as our ISO file later on we will do this practical very\nsoon, where in we will create our own ISO file, we will package them and we will use them becuase there are\nparticular use cases where we need to package our ISO file and to use them to launch a instance. We will be\ndoing that also. We will discuss the use case of this later.\n\nNow after selecting Ubuntu we will see this is giving basic like howmuch SSD attached or what is the HDD\ntype, Hardisk type is SSD.\n\nNow we will select instance type make sure free tier eligible\nWhat is this instance type -> \n    there are multiple type available likt t type to i type etc\n    one type is\n        t3.micro -> 3 part -> t, 3, micro\n            micro -> whatever this part micro, nano, large, x large, 2 x large, 4x large, this refers to size\n            which meand how big or how small our instance will be, basically howmany core of CPU, \n            howmuch RAM, howmany processors are going to be there, Howmuch HDD is going to be there,\n            what is the network bandwidth my system will use, Based on that we decide and we call it\n            as size of my system.\n\n            3 ->  this is basically what version of t is this. it is older version or newer version\n            it will give you that. So older versions are bit stale and all of that t3 is comparativly\n            a newer one. so we can use t3 rather than using t2, if it is showing free tier on\n            t3.\n\n            t -> this shows us instance type. like is it good for test purpose or do we want to\n                launch a application which is very GPU heavy then we can use g type instance.\n                if the task is IO intensive means better quality RAM is needed , then we will use\n                IO based instance i type instance, which means my input output speed will be very fast. My RAM speed\n                will be very fast.\n\n                m type is memory based instance. when there is too much of memory work. Likewise\n                there are multiple type and catrgory created based on our usecase.\n\n            Right now as we are working on test environment we will take t type with basic hardware.\n            t3.micro\n\nNext thing is key pair ->\n    In AWS servers we dont usually login via id and password, we have a user created and for \n    that user we have a key assigned to it. SSH key assigned to it. this is a public key\n    private key mechanism of Cryptography.\n    So we will create a new key pair, this key will help us to have a pem file, that pem file we can use\n    that public key file we can use to login to my server.\n\nNext we need to select our network ->\n    now this part works more or less like a firewall.\n    this is very interesting part\n    \n    first af all look at -> Auto Assign Public IP is enabled which says our VM whatever we create will \n    automatically be allocated a public IP address.\n       \n    AWS is very interesting and very business minded in this sence. So when we create a instance and we \n    want to assign public IP to it. or if we want to block a public IP for ourself even without creating \n    a instance. they will allow us to get or have public IPs. They would not charge to us untill and unless\n    we are using it with the instance. they will only charge us when we are blocking a IP or when we are\n    keeping the IP to ourself without attaching it to a instance.\n\n    Why it is a great business trick? -> \n       It looks like they are giving something as free when we are using it but this is not free. becuase to \n        use this IP we have to use it with the instance. Means first we need to create instance that money\n        we need to keep on running that instance we need to pay for that\n        Now we have IP and users and everything, Users will come to us via IP, So they will charge us on\n        network bandwidth's incoming and outgoing of our resources. they will charge us on that like howmuch\n        data transaction is there. howmuch data is transferring they will charge us on that.\n        So they earn not by making sure that they have given us a public IP but making sure that they create\n        a mechanism where we constantly use a public IP address.\n\n    \n    \n    Now we can set firewall rule like allow it from anywhere in the world, From anywhere in world allow \n    everyone to SSH, everyone to connect on HTTP, everyone to connect on HTTPS if and only if they have\n    the key. because there is a key based login.\n    For SSH there is key based logoi for HTTP and HTTPs anyways they can reach out.\n\nNext we need to configure Storage -> \n    what HDD we need, if we want to attach a additional HDD we can attach over there, they will attach something\n    as sdb.\n\nthese are required for now, we will talk other details also when we advance the concept of VMs.\n\nNow after launching instance, once status check is done, now to connect with this system there are few way\nwe can either use pem file using our linux terminal, if we are in windows there are softwares called as\nputty, we can use this software that will give us a terminal from where we can connect to our AWS intance.\nor there are softwares like mobaxterm we can use this also it can allow us to run multiple session at\nthe similar time on the same EC2 also.\nEasiest way is connect direcly via browser using the feature that AWS provides to us. we can connect via\nssh or we can connect direcly via EC2 instance connect(click on connect on the instance), and hit connect\nand now we can see this will open terminal directly. this is the same Ubuntu terminal that we get in VM.\nEC2 is not only about creating VMs.\n\nNow delete the instance\n    instance state ->     terminate(delete) instance\n\n\nNow we will talk about few interesting services that we will talk about, we can see that instances is one of\nthe service that comes under the hood of EC2, But there are other services also which are very imp one.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "We all with start with IAAS for this purpose\n1 login to cloud account or root user\n2 make sure we are in our nearest region if we are in India we must be in mumbai region (APAC) asia\n    pasific region\n3 Now we will create our 1st EC2(Elastic Compute Cloud) instance, search in services for EC2 and go inside that then in\n    dashboard we get launch instance\n    one way is we can crate EC2 instance by launching instance\n    second way is we can check if there is any existing instance, existing VMs created or not, In terminology\n    of AWS we will call our VMs as our instance. \n    \n    for new instance we will click on launch instance\n    \n    give name -> tryserver or anything that we want to give\n\n    second thing is when we have installed Virtual Machine, we didn't only need Oracle Virtual Box or any\nhypervisor we also needed something called as a ISO file.\nwe can choose our ISO, here we will choose Ubuntu  as our ISO file later on we will do this practical very\nsoon, where in we will create our own ISO file, we will package them and we will use them becuase there are\nparticular use cases where we need to package our ISO file and to use them to launch a instance. We will be\ndoing that also. We will discuss the use case of this later.\n\nNow after selecting Ubuntu we will see this is giving basic like howmuch SSD attached or what is the HDD\ntype, Hardisk type is SSD.\n\nNow we will select instance type make sure free tier eligible\nWhat is this instance type -> \n    there are multiple type available likt t type to i type etc\n    one type is\n        t3.micro -> 3 part -> t, 3, micro\n            micro -> whatever this part micro, nano, large, x large, 2 x large, 4x large, this refers to size\n            which meand how big or how small our instance will be, basically howmany core of CPU, \n            howmuch RAM, howmany processors are going to be there, Howmuch HDD is going to be there,\n            what is the network