      "updated": 1773749206350,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Q -> Now we will try to deploy a website on VM(entance (IAAS)), And then understand where are the other\nfeatures of cloud that can help or which ones are the other features of cloud that can help us improvise\nthat deployment.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Q -> Now we will try to deploy a website on VM(entance (IAAS)), And then understand where are the other\nfeatures of cloud that can help or which ones are the other features of cloud that can help us improvise\nthat deployment.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "U8aOD8UiT7yI2MBARkdnt",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1294.547920796342,
      "y": 49709.96974580291,
      "width": 1221,
      "height": 675,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bd8",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1042206742,
      "version": 2177,
      "versionNonce": 294553174,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773750673675,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1 Login into AWS account using root user.\n2 Launch Ubuntu based EC2 instance, also we need to make sure while launching port 80 and 22 are\n    open or they are allowed.\n3 Make sure public IP is enabled, by default it is enabled but make sure it is enabled\n4 Make sure whatever we are doing, it has to be in our nearest location data center\n5 connect with instance (Easy way) EC2 instance connect\n6 run first command whoami -> it will give ubuntu it is fine as ubuntu has root permissions\n7 update and upgrade your repositories.\n    sudo apt update\n    sudo apt upgrade -y\n8 install web server -> apache 2\n    sudo apt install apache2 -y\n    once apahe2 is instaled the cache here is that it might work or might not work right now.\n    \n    IN linux if any command is not working there are some issues or problem with the command\n    1 -> our command or flag(parameter) is not right we are doing a typo.\n    2 -> second reason could be command is not installed. for example if we will uninstall date, \n        then no matter how much we will try and run date it will not work.\n    3 -> third reason could be path is not set. when ever we write any command like man, date or\n        anything, obviously there is a code behind it. and that code usually kept in /bin  or\n        /sbin or /user/bin or /user/sbin or may be in current location ., if that is in current location\n         then it will work even if we will not give path.\n      Our command can't check in whole system, it will be checked in some specific locations like\n        /sbin or /user/bin or /user/sbin or /bin\n     and how it is going to check, there is a variable called as path, OS uses this variable which is\n    called as path. not in this PATH whatever location we are giving, suppose we have give /bin:/sbin:/usr/bin \n    if we want to give our own path then we can add that path here also.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1 Login into AWS account using root user.\n2 Launch Ubuntu based EC2 instance, also we need to make sure while launching port 80 and 22 are\n    open or they are allowed.\n3 Make sure public IP is enabled, by default it is enabled but make sure it is enabled\n4 Make sure whatever we are doing, it has to be in our nearest location data center\n5 connect with instance (Easy way) EC2 instance connect\n6 run first command whoami -> it will give ubuntu it is fine as ubuntu has root permissions\n7 update and upgrade your repositories.\n    sudo apt update\n    sudo apt upgrade -y\n8 install web server -> apache 2\n    sudo apt install apache2 -y\n    once apahe2 is instaled the cache here is that it might work or might not work right now.\n    \n    IN linux if any command is not working there are some issues or problem with the command\n    1 -> our command or flag(parameter) is not right we are doing a typo.\n    2 -> second reason could be command is not installed. for example if we will uninstall date, \n        then no matter how much we will try and run date it will not work.\n    3 -> third reason could be path is not set. when ever we write any command like man, date or\n        anything, obviously there is a code behind it. and that code usually kept in /bin  or\n        /sbin or /user/bin or /user/sbin or may be in current location ., if that is in current location\n         then it will work even if we will not give path.\n      Our command can't check in whole system, it will be checked in some specific locations like\n        /sbin or /user/bin or /user/sbin or /bin\n     and how it is going to check, there is a variable called as path, OS uses this variable which is\n    called as path. not in this PATH whatever location we are giving, suppose we have give /bin:/sbin:/usr/bin \n    if we want to give our own path then we can add that path here also.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "XodQA0yM6Fsx0DOzBVDqj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1362.047920796342,
      "y": 50415.00099580291,
      "width": 1210,
      "height": 75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bd9",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 699578250,
      "version": 382,
      "versionNonce": 612753866,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773750851793,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How the software gets installed or how is it know from where it has to pick Apache2, it can take anywhere\nfrom internet, but it would not. there are certain specific locations on internet where it will go and try to \nsee your software is there or not, those locations are called as our Repo or Repositories.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How the software gets installed or how is it know from where it has to pick Apache2, it can take anywhere\nfrom internet, but it would not. there are certain specific locations on internet where it will go and try to \nsee your software is there or not, those locations are called as our Repo or Repositories.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "meDkkjiIlPkSQ1WbbGHLM",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1413.723702046342,
      "y": 50507.36818330291,
      "width": 1188,
      "height": 125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bdA",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2023454538,
      "version": 580,
      "versionNonce": 853127178,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773751053838,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "these repo are specific locations that keep all the software packages. It will get downloaded from there\nand installed from there, Again how there locations will be known, there are files called as repo files\nin there repo files we can edit or add multiple locations, once we will add those locations, our system will\ngo, our apt command will go, check on that repo file and it will go on the location, it will try to find\nApache2 software exists there or not. if it is there it will download and install.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "these repo are specific locations that keep all the software packages. It will get downloaded from there\nand installed from there, Again how there locations will be known, there are files called as repo files\nin there repo files we can edit or add multiple locations, once we will add those locations, our system will\ngo, our apt command will go, check on that repo file and it will go on the location, it will try to find\nApache2 software exists there or not. if it is there it will download and install.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "qIZoJQDDVEDlbZD-gxQu7",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1306.868233296342,
      "y": 50690.95412080291,
      "width": 1188,
      "height": 250,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bdB",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1865859094,
      "version": 966,
      "versionNonce": 2144535562,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773751493981,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "    4 Permission issue\n    5 Service is not running ->\n        All the software not work like we will call and they will give response, date software work like\n        this we call date it will display date and it will exit.\n        but lets say there is a software like webserver Apache2, Now we can't say that I have a system, when\n        a user comes that time my server will start, it will set all the webpages, it will connect to \n        everything the backend and all and then it will generate a response. No It has to keep on running\n        so that whenever user comes, based on requirement of user it is already connected with backend and\n        everything and it can generate my response. these kind of services or software when we put them in\n        background and they keep on running they are called as demon process",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "    4 Permission issue\n    5 Service is not running ->\n        All the software not work like we will call and they will give response, date software work like\n        this we call date it will display date and it will exit.\n        but lets say there is a software like webserver Apache2, Now we can't say that I have a system, when\n        a user comes that time my server will start, it will set all the webpages, it will connect to \n        everything the backend and all and then it will generate a response. No It has to keep on running\n        so that whenever user comes, based on requirement of user it is already connected with backend and\n        everything and it can generate my response. these kind of services or software when we put them in\n        background and they keep on running they are called as demon process",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "pw2Cncca0lE8bJmN4meP9",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1288.477608296342,
      "y": 51000.43068330291,
      "width": 1100,
      "height": 600,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bdC",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1513813718,
      "version": 1218,
      "versionNonce": 953720010,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773752904749,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "9 Once Apache2 is installed, we need to make sure that demon process of Apache 2 is also running\n  To check that command is\n    sudo systemctl status apache2 -> if the status is active then it is fine\n\n    if it is not active what we can do\n    sudo systemctl start apache2\n    sudo systemctl enable apache2\n     \n    start will start the server now in current session, enable puts it on boot so that if later on\n    we will create image of this machine, and again we run this AMI instance then everytime on\n    boot it is running again.\n     \n    if we will not run enable just start run then everytime on rebooting we need to start manually.\n    As we dont want manual start this again and again so we are putting this on boot.\n    \n    we can set firewall rule for Apache using below commands\n    \n    sudo ufw allow 'Apache'\n    sudo ufw enable\n    sudo ufw status\n\n10 run in browser\n    http://public ip -> if the http is not allowed then this site will not reached otherwise it will\n            give apache page.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "9 Once Apache2 is installed, we need to make sure that demon process of Apache 2 is also running\n  To check that command is\n    sudo systemctl status apache2 -> if the status is active then it is fine\n\n    if it is not active what we can do\n    sudo systemctl start apache2\n    sudo systemctl enable apache2\n     \n    start will start the server now in current session, enable puts it on boot so that if later on\n    we will create image of this machine, and again we run this AMI instance then everytime on\n    boot it is running again.\n     \n    if we will not run enable just start run then everytime on rebooting we need to start manually.\n    As we dont want manual start this again and again so we are putting this on boot.\n    \n    we can set firewall rule for Apache using below commands\n    \n    sudo ufw allow 'Apache'\n    sudo ufw enable\n    sudo ufw status\n\n10 run in browser\n    http://public ip -> if the http is not allowed then this site will not reached otherwise it will\n            give apache page.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
