    },
    {
      "id": "pBBj-Gf-a5hrTquun0hk1",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1812.325264546342,
      "y": 52858.13771455291,
      "width": 814,
      "height": 750,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bdQ",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1763112202,
      "version": 1235,
      "versionNonce": 969869834,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773771125062,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "One instance can respond to limited set of users\ndue to network capabilities and other things, probably\nlets say 500 or 1000 people it can respond\n\nIn that case what we try and do is that we try to setup\nmultiple instances\n\nMultiple instances that have the same web server.\n\nthe problem here is that if we will setup multiple instances\nlets say we are setting for google.com\n\nif google sets up these many instances imagine howmany IPs,\nhowmany public Ips it has to give to the Authorative Name\nServer(ANS)\n\nWhat Google or anyone does ?\n    they would not allow public directly to come to their\ninstance, like here we have allowed public entry using\n0.0.0.0/0 that entry will not allowed.\n\nthey will have another machine, now the user will come and connect to\nthis machine, No matter howmany users are there, they will come to this\nmachine and connect, this machine dont have any webserver, it doesn't have\nanything like Apache or anything.\n\nwhat this machine will do is, it will redirect one by one all the users\nto these instances\n\nthis machine or architecture is called as Load Balancer.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "One instance can respond to limited set of users\ndue to network capabilities and other things, probably\nlets say 500 or 1000 people it can respond\n\nIn that case what we try and do is that we try to setup\nmultiple instances\n\nMultiple instances that have the same web server.\n\nthe problem here is that if we will setup multiple instances\nlets say we are setting for google.com\n\nif google sets up these many instances imagine howmany IPs,\nhowmany public Ips it has to give to the Authorative Name\nServer(ANS)\n\nWhat Google or anyone does ?\n    they would not allow public directly to come to their\ninstance, like here we have allowed public entry using\n0.0.0.0/0 that entry will not allowed.\n\nthey will have another machine, now the user will come and connect to\nthis machine, No matter howmany users are there, they will come to this\nmachine and connect, this machine dont have any webserver, it doesn't have\nanything like Apache or anything.\n\nwhat this machine will do is, it will redirect one by one all the users\nto these instances\n\nthis machine or architecture is called as Load Balancer.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
