    },
    {
      "id": "gfsKGujRB4ZigbuBuZG4L",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1161.792413767107,
      "y": 59079.11169165083,
      "width": 1067,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ber",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1622521696,
      "version": 838,
      "versionNonce": 745897824,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773832569039,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "It basically works on Network Layer Protocol\nWhat are network Layer Protocols ?\n    tcp, udp\n\nWhen a packet gets created, In a packet various layers are there, and each layes has some info\nrelated to a specific layer of OSI model\n\nSo basically packets contains certain level, and certain level has certain detail over there, So\nwhy to strip every time and read, If I know the exact location where my info is,\nNetwork LB knows exactly at which location on the packet my TCP or UDP will be mentioned.\n\nApplication LB knows where http or https and all of that info will be mentioned. So they will \ndirectly go there rather than stripping the packet and then finding out they will directly go and\nread the required detail and route the packet.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "It basically works on Network Layer Protocol\nWhat are network Layer Protocols ?\n    tcp, udp\n\nWhen a packet gets created, In a packet various layers are there, and each layes has some info\nrelated to a specific layer of OSI model\n\nSo basically packets contains certain level, and certain level has certain detail over there, So\nwhy to strip every time and read, If I know the exact location where my info is,\nNetwork LB knows exactly at which location on the packet my TCP or UDP will be mentioned.\n\nApplication LB knows where http or https and all of that info will be mentioned. So they will \ndirectly go there rather than stripping the packet and then finding out they will directly go and\nread the required detail and route the packet.",
