    },
    {
      "id": "na4GErCnuOHTEqs_UFrvG",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1536.622139546342,
      "y": 79213.93068330291,
      "width": 1100,
      "height": 550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bmH",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 897558626,
      "version": 1614,
      "versionNonce": 1543663742,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776277505781,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "secures shell -> it is used to get access to the remote server.\nwe thing it will provide as a shell but technically it is not.\n\nssh -p password -i user@ip1(ip that we want to ssh on), this is how we generally ssh. after that\n    as a output we will get shell will be of this ip ip1.\n    IP1$ -> why we get this shell is because, when I am doing this, at the end ssh by itself over\n        ip shell adds one command which is /bin/bash  or /bin/sh or whatever depend on the ssh\n        version or the user shell. that shell comes over here by default. which means it will go to\n        the IP1 instance and it will run command /bin/bash, when we run this command it will give\n        us the output of /bin/bash and which is the output itself is a shell where in we can now\n        keep on running commands till we exit.\n    \n        So actually what is my ssh doing -> ssh is just going to IP1 and running a command /bin/bash\n        and giving us the ouput back on my system.\n        \n        But we see it as that I am getting a whole terminal. It is just one command inside which we \n        are executing multiple commands. so what If we replace this /bin/bash totally with date. we\n        will get output of date command but that date will be date on another system.\n\n    ssh -p password -i user@ip1 date -> then we will get date of IP1 system\n    ssh -p password -i user@ip1 hostname -i -> then we will get ip of IP1 system\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "secures shell -> it is used to get access to the remote server.\nwe thing it will provide as a shell but technically it is not.\n\nssh -p password -i user@ip1(ip that we want to ssh on), this is how we generally ssh. after that\n    as a output we will get shell will be of this ip ip1.\n    IP1$ -> why we get this shell is because, when I am doing this, at the end ssh by itself over\n        ip shell adds one command which is /bin/bash  or /bin/sh or whatever depend on the ssh\n        version or the user shell. that shell comes over here by default. which means it will go to\n        the IP1 instance and it will run command /bin/bash, when we run this command it will give\n        us the output of /bin/bash and which is the output itself is a shell where in we can now\n        keep on running commands till we exit.\n    \n        So actually what is my ssh doing -> ssh is just going to IP1 and running a command /bin/bash\n        and giving us the ouput back on my system.\n        \n        But we see it as that I am getting a whole terminal. It is just one command inside which we \n        are executing multiple commands. so what If we replace this /bin/bash totally with date. we\n        will get output of date command but that date will be date on another system.\n\n    ssh -p password -i user@ip1 date -> then we will get date of IP1 system\n    ssh -p password -i user@ip1 hostname -i -> then we will get ip of IP1 system\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
